---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Workshops"
  description="Hands-on AI workshops for individuals, teams, and companies — public sessions and private in-house workshops — plus the implementation work that follows."
>
  <div class="container-wide">
    <section class="section-band">
      <div class="panel workbench-hero-copy services-hero-full">
        <p class="eyebrow">AI workshops, public and private</p>
        <h1>AI that actually does your work.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Hands-on workshops where you build a working AI assistant from your own tools, files, reusable workflows, and human approval gates.
          You leave with something real, not a prompt-library talk. Run one for yourself, your team, or your whole company.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-links" style="justify-content: flex-start;">
          <a href="/contact/" class="hero-btn">Bring a workshop to your company</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>The Workshops</h2>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill blue">Public</span>
          <h3>Build your own AI assistant</h3>
          <p>A hands-on session for individuals and small teams. You leave with a working personal assistant, reusable workflows you ran yourself, connected tools where it's safe, and a clear next step.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill plum">Private / company</span>
          <h3>In-house team workshop</h3>
          <p>The same hands-on build, run privately for your company against your real processes. A low-risk way to get a team unstuck and see exactly where AI fits the way you already work.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Who This Is For</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        This is for people who want practical automation judgment and a thing that works by the end of the session, not a generic AI overview.
        The same hands-on approach serves a curious founder, an SMB operations team, or an enterprise group rolling out automation across finance, HR, IT, operations, sales, or marketing.
      </p>
      <p class="cred-line">
        Grounded in 20+ years in enterprise technology, including years inside automation adoption: discovery workshops, stakeholder alignment, governance, queues, operating models, and delivery across business and technical teams.
      </p>
      <div class="proof-strip">
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill blue">Individuals</span>
          <strong>People who want to actually use AI</strong>
          <p>You've experimented with Claude, ChatGPT, or agents but haven't turned it into something repeatable. Leave with a working assistant and the workflows behind it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill sage">Teams</span>
          <strong>Teams stuck at individual tinkering</strong>
          <p>Manual reporting, queue work, repeated research, intake triage, approvals, or process knowledge stuck in people's heads. We turn it into shared, reviewable workflows.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill plum">Companies</span>
          <strong>Companies evaluating AI seriously</strong>
          <p>A private workshop is a low-risk first step: get hands-on with your real processes, then decide where a deeper implementation is worth it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>What You Leave With</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Every workshop is built to produce something real by the time you leave, not notes to act on later.
      </p>
      <div class="utility-grid outcome-grid">
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>A working assistant</strong>
          <p>An AI assistant configured to your role, priorities, and voice, with the right human approval gates so it drafts and assists without acting unsupervised.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Reusable workflows</strong>
          <p>Saved, repeatable workflows you ran at least twice yourself: research, morning brief, meeting prep, triage. Not one-off prompts you'll forget.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>A clear next step</strong>
          <p>A resource pack and an honest read on which of your processes is worth turning into real automation, and which to leave alone.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band" id="expansion">
      <h2>After the Workshop: Turn It Into Working Automation</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Workshops are the front door. When a process is clearly worth it, the next step is implementation: for an individual, a team, or across the company. It starts with mapping one real workflow before anyone buys a tool or builds a demo.
      </p>
      <div class="callout offer-callout">
        <p class="eyebrow">AI Workflow Friction Map</p>
        <h3>A 45-60 minute working session before anyone buys a tool or builds a demo.</h3>
        <p>
          Best when a team has a process with visible drag: repeated intake, manual reporting, queue work, approvals, research, handoffs, or decisions that keep getting re-litigated.
        </p>
        <p>
          The output is a practical pilot map: current flow, bottlenecks, candidate AI assists, review points, implementation risks, and the clearest next build.
          This is intentionally not a prompt-library session, a magic-agent promise, or a vague AI transformation deck.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-roadmap">
        <article class="panel process-step agent" data-step="01">
          <div class="eyebrow">Discovery</div>
          <h3>Map the operation</h3>
          <p>Run process workshops, identify bottlenecks, capture handoffs, surface exceptions, and score automation opportunities by value, risk, and readiness.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step guardrail" data-step="02">
          <div class="eyebrow">Advisory</div>
          <h3>Design the system</h3>
          <p>Translate the map into architecture, tool choices, governance, human review points, success measures, and a buildable implementation scope.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step review" data-step="03">
          <div class="eyebrow">Build</div>
          <h3>Ship the first use case</h3>
          <p>Build or guide the first useful automation system: intake, routing, agent instructions, data flow, review artifacts, and operating documentation.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>The Full Engagement Path</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Most people start with a workshop and stop there with something useful. When the work justifies it, the path continues into hands-on implementation.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill blue">Workshop</span>
          <h3>Public or private workshop</h3>
          <p>The front door. Get hands-on, build something that works, and see where AI fits your real work before committing to anything bigger.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill sage">Map</span>
          <h3>AI Workflow Friction Map</h3>
          <p>When a process is worth it: a focused session that produces a prioritized pilot map, constraints, review gates, and the clearest next build.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill copper">Sprint</span>
          <h3>Pilot &amp; build sprints</h3>
          <p>Turn the map into a working system: internal tools, agent workflows, automation scripts, reporting systems, knowledge assistants, or review systems.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill plum">Advisory</span>
          <h3>Implementation advisory</h3>
          <p>For leadership and delivery teams: architecture, vendor/tool choices, governance, rollout sequencing, and ongoing prioritization as automation scales.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band service-cta">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Start with a workshop</p>
        <h2>Want a working assistant, or a whole team that can build them?</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          Join a public workshop and build your own, or bring a private one in-house for your team. Tell me what you want to build and I will help find the right format and the right next step.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="service-cta-actions">
        <a href="/contact/" class="hero-btn">Bring a workshop to your company</a>
        <a href="/projects/" class="hero-btn hero-btn-outline">See project work</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
